<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-BootstrapDist" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Bootstrap Distributions</title>
  <introduction>
    <p> Previously we discussed creating a sampling distribution from a known population. In this section we are working in the other direction. Often, we do not know the details of the population, but we are able to gather a sample. We will be using information from a single sample to understand what is true about the population. </p>
  </introduction>
 
<objectives>
  <introduction>
    <p> At the end of this section you will be able to:   </p>
  </introduction>
  <ol>
    <li> <p> Construct and interpret a bootstrap distribution for the mean.</p>    </li>
    <li> <p> Construct and interpret a bootstrap distribution for proportions.</p> </li>
        
</ol>
</objectives>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-BootstrapMeans">
  <title>Bootstrap Distributions for Means</title>

  <p> Previously we constructed sampling distributions based on population parameters we already know by taking thousands of different samples. However, in most situations we do not know the value of population parameters and we do not have the resources to take multiple samples. </p>
<p>In this section we introduce a method for estimating the variability of statistic that uses only the data in the original sample - by sampling with replacement. This will allow us to approximate the sampling distribution and construct confidence intervals.</p>

<p>Recently there has been an increase in awareness of fuel economy and more options for electric vehicles. We are going to investigate a sample of cars to predict how energy efficient they are. MPGe (miles per gallon equivalent) is the measurement used to track the efficiency of electric vehicles (EVs), similar to the way MPG (miles per gallon) measures regular gas-powered cars. </p>
<p>Devised by the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), MPGe uses the exact amount of electric energy equal to the energy in one gallon of gasoline and then looks at the distance that a specific electric vehicle travels on that amount of energy. </p>
<p> What is the typical MPGe of newer models of EVs? </p>
<p>To answer the question, a curious electric vehicle enthusiast obtained the following random sample of the MPGe of EVs from 2023:</p> 
<ul>
<li> <p> Tesla Model X Plaid - 91 MPGe </p> </li>
<li> <p> Jaguar I-Pace EV400 - 85 MPGe </p> </li>
<li> <p> Polestar 2 Single Motor - 107 MPGe </p> </li>
<li> <p> Lucid Air Pure AWD - 140 MPGe </p> </li>
<li> <p> Lordstown Endurance - 48 MPGe </p> </li>
</ul> 

<p> We are going to simulate creating a sampling distribution but using just this one sample of five cars. This process is known as generating a bootstrap distribution. </p>
<p> To generate a bootstrap distribution, we: </p>
<ol>
<li> <p> Generate bootstrap samples by sampling with replacement from the original sample, using the same sample size. </p> </li>
<li> <p> Compute the statistic of interest, called a bootstrap statistic, for each of the bootstrap samples. </p> </li>
<li> <p> Collect the statistics for many bootstrap samples to create a bootstrap distribution. </p> </li>
</ol> 
<p> To illustrate this process: List each car on a note card with its MPGe. Randomly select a card, note the MPGE for the car, then replace the card to the deck. Shuffle the cards. Repeat the process until you have a sample of 5 cars. Find the average value of the five cars then plot the point to begin the distribution. Keep repeating this process until we have a bootstrap distribution of the sample means.</p> 
<p> The purpose of replacing the card is to give us some variability in the samples we select. If we use the same 5 cars each time, there is no variation. </p> 

<p> Give example </p> 
<p> To have enough samples to get a bell-shaped distribution will take time. We would likely need thousands of samples of size 5. But we can simulate this process with technology. </p> 

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-BootTechnologyMean">
  <title>Using Technology: Mean</title>

<p> Open <term> StatKey </term> and in the middle column under <term> Bootstrap Confidence Intervals </term> we are going to select  <term> CI for Single Mean </term>. </p> 
<figure xml:id="BootstrapMenu">
            <caption> Bootstrap Menu </caption>
            <image source="boot1.png" >
                <shortdescription>first option in second column is bootstrap for the mean.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure> 
<p> Click on the <c> Upload File </c> button and identify the data file: <em>EV2023-Sample5 </em> and select the variable <em> CombMPGe</em> .</p>
<figure xml:id="BootstrapMenuOptions">
            <caption> Bootstrap for Mean </caption>
            <image source="Boot2.png" >
                <shortdescription>fourth option is to upload the file.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>
<p> Interpreting StatKey: On the top right side you will see the <term>Original Sample</term> information. The sample of 5 cards has a mean MPGe of 94.2, median 91, and standard deviation of 33.507. </p>
<p> If we click on the <c> Generate 1 Sample </c> button, then on the bottom right side we will see the five randomly selected cars with replacement under the <term> Bootstrap Sample </term> . For this sample the mean is 80, the median is 85, and the standard deviation is 18.138. The mean of 80 which is plotted on the Bootstrap Dotplot. Continue generating samples until you have generated at least 500 samples. </p> 
<figure xml:id="BootstrapMPGe">
            <caption> Bootstrap MPGe for 501 Samples </caption>
            <image source="Boot3.png" >
                <shortdescription>dotplot of 501 dots for average car mileage with values between 60 and 130 centered at 93.671.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>
<p> Interpreting StatKey: The Bootstrap Dot plot has 501 samples of the average MPGe for 5 electric vehicles. The distribution is approximately bell shaped and centered at the mean 93.671 and the standard error is 12.797. So using this sample data, we would predict the population mean to be around 93-94 MPGe for electric vehicles from 2023. </p> 

<p> <term> Exploration </term> </p> 
<p> Now it's time for you to explore the data. You can continue working with the MPGe or you can choose one of the built-in data sets. </p> 
<exercise>
    <statement> 
<p> As you generate more samples, what happens to the shape of the distribution? </p></statement>
<solution> <p> Notice how the distribution becomes more bell shaped and symmetric with more samples. The center of the distribution is approximately the same as the original sample mean. </p> </solution>
</exercise> 

<exercise> <statement>
<p> Where is the center of the distribution? </p></statement>
<solution> <p> The center of the bootstrap distribution is approximately the same as the original sample mean.  </p> </solution> 
</exercise> 

<exercise> <statement>
<p> Compare the standard deviation of the original sample to the standard error of the distribution. </p></statement> 
<solution> <p> The standard error is smaller since there is less variation with the distribution than a single sample.  </p> </solution> 
</exercise> 

<p> Just as our samples have variation, we do not want just a single number to represent the typical population value, we want an interval to estimate the likely values our parameter will take. Thus we look at creating an interval to predict the parameter. </p> 
<p> When a bootstrap distribution for a sample statistic is symmetric and bell-shaped, we estimate a 95% confidence interval using <term> statistics </term> <m>  \pm 2 \bullet  SE </m>   where SE denotes the standard error of the statistic estimated from the bootstrap distribution. </p> 
<p> Using the original sample mean of 94.2 and the standard error of the bootstrap distribution of 12.797 this gives </p>
<p> <md> \text {mean} \pm 2 \bullet SE </md>  </p>
<p> <md> 94.2 \pm 2 (12.797) </md></p>
<p> <md> 94.2 \pm 25.594 </md> </p>
<p> <md> (68.606, 119.794) </md> </p>
<p> We can be 95% confidence that the mean combined MPGe for all electric vehicles in 2023 is between 68.6 and 119.8 miles. </p> 

<p> If we click on <c>Two Tail </c> we can select .95 to create a 95% confidence interval of our predicted mean value for the population using our bootstrap distribution. We can be 95% confident that the mean combined MPGe for all electric vehicles in 2023 is between 67.2 and 117.0 miles. </p> 
<figure xml:id="BootstrapCIMPGe1">
            <caption> Bootstrap Interval for MPGe </caption>
            <image source="Boot4.png" >
                <shortdescription>Middle 95% of dots between 67.2 and 117 MPGe.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>

<p> If we change the middle percentage to .90 to represent the middle 90% of the values in the distribution, our interval is now from 71.6 to 113.14 MPGe for the electric vehicles in 2023.</p> 
<figure xml:id="BootstrapCIMPGe2">
            <caption> Bootstrap Interval for MPGe </caption>
            <image source="Boot5.png" >
                <shortdescription>Middle 90% of dots between 71.6 and 113.14 MPGe.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>

<p> <term> Exploration </term> </p> 
<p> Now it's time for you to explore what impacts the intervals in the bootstrap distribution. You can continue working with the MPGe or you can choose one of the built-in data sets. </p> 
<exercise>
    <statement>
<p> Choose a specific confidence level (such as 95%), as you generate more samples, what happens to the interval? You will need to keep changing the middle percentage to .95 or your designed level each time you re-evaluate the interval </p></statement> 
<solution> <p> Once the distribution appears bell-shaped and symmetric, the interval values do not change much by generating additional samples. This may vary by how much variation there is in the original sample.</p> </solution>
</exercise> 
<exercise> <statement>
<p> Generate a bootstrap distribution. Keep the number of samples the same. Compare what happens to the interval when you go from 50% to 70% to 90% of the values in the middle. </p></statement> 
<solution> <p> As the middle percentage increases, the interval becomes wider since it includes more values in the interval.  </p> </solution> 
</exercise> 
<exercise>
    <statement>
    <p> Generate a bootstrap distribution. Keep the number of samples the same. Compare what happens to the interval when you go from 95% to 85% to 75% of the values in the middle. </p>
    </statement>
    <solution> <p> As the middle percentage decreases, the interval becomes narrower since it includes fewer values in the interval.  </p> </solution> 
</exercise> 
<exercise>
    <statement>
     <p> What happens to the standard error as you increase the number of samples. </p>
    </statement>
    <solution> <p> The standard error does not change much by adding generating additional samples.  </p> </solution> 
</exercise> 



</subsection>



<subsection xml:id="subsec-BootstrapProportions">
  <title> Bootstrap Distributions for Proportions</title>

<p>Suppose you want to find what proportion of Skittles  are grape flavored in a typical bag. So you enlist the help of your friends. You and each of your friends buy a bag of Skittles and count how many are grape out of the total number in the bag. Each person calculates the proportion that are grape and plots them on a graph to create a distribution. </p>
<p> Since each person has their own bag of candy, each sample is independent of the others and taken from the population of all Skittles candy. We will assume each bag has the same number of candies. Below is a bootstrap distribution from 2.17 ounce bags of Skittles candy for the proportion that is grape. </p> 

<figure xml:id="BootstrapSkittle1">
            <caption> Bootstrap For 10 Bags </caption>
            <image source="BootSkittle1.png" >
                <shortdescription>proportions between 12.5% and 25% grape .</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>
<p> This distribution of ten bags is centered at 16.6% for the proportion of grape Skittles, with values ranging from 12.5% to 25%. </p> 

<figure xml:id="BootstrapSkittle2">
            <caption> Bootstrap For 250 Bags </caption>
            <image source="BootSkittle2.png" >
                <shortdescription>proportions between 8% and 32% grape with higher frequencies at the center near 0.183.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>

<p> This simulated distribution is for 250 bags of Skittles. The proportion of grapes is centered at 0.183 with standard error of 0.048. With 250 samples, the bootstrap distribution is symmetric and bell shaped. Based on this distribution, we would predict that the proportion of grape Skittles is around 18.3%. </p> 

  </subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-BootTechnologyProp">
  <title>Using Technology: Proportions</title>
  <p> Using StatKey to construct bootstrap distributions from a single proportion. </p> 
<p> Launch <term>StatKey</term>, and from the center column under <term>Bootstrap Confidence Intervals</term>, select the second option <term>CI for Single Proportion</term>. </p> 
<figure xml:id="BootstrapSkittle3">
            <caption> StatKey Menu </caption>
            <image source="BootSkittle3.png" >
                <shortdescription>select the second option under Bootstrap Confidence Intervals .</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>
<p> Click on <c>Edit Data</c> and enter the count of 12 grape from a sample size of 65 candies and then click <c>OK</c> </p>
<figure xml:id="BootstrapSkittle4">
            <caption> Edit Proportion </caption>
            <image source="BootSkittle4.png" >
                <shortdescription>use the second table for Edit Data and enter the count 12 and sample size 65. Then click ok .</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>
<p> Click on <c> Generate 1 Sample</c>. On the right side of the screen, it will identify how many grape in a sample of 65 candies and plots the proportion on the graph. This simulates the proportion of grape flavored candies for each bag of 65 candies. Each new sample simulates the proportion from one of your friends. </p>

<figure xml:id="BootstrapSkittle5">
            <caption> Generate Bootstrap Sample </caption>
            <image source="BootSkittle5.png" >
                <shortdescription>one sample of 65 Skittles has 17 grapes and plots proportion 0.262 on the graph .</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>
<p> Continue generating samples until you have a bell-shaped distribution. You may need 500 samples. The image below shows how the values are centered at 0.184 with values ranging from 4/65=0.062 to 23/65=0.354. If you click on a dot, the Bootstrap Sample count and proportion will show on the right. The mean proportion is 0.184 with the standard error of 0.047. </p> 

<figure xml:id="BootstrapSkittle6">
            <caption> Generate Bootstrap Distribution </caption>
            <image source="BootSkittle6.png" >
                <shortdescription>500 dots representing the proportion of grapes for each bag .</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>

<p> If you click on <c>Two-Tail</c> it constructs the 95% confidence interval. Reading the values along the bottom of the screen we are predict the true proportion of grape Skittles is between 10.8% and 27.7% based on this simulated bootstrap distribution. </p> 
<figure xml:id="BootstrapSkittle7">
            <caption> Bootstrap Confidence Interval</caption>
            <image source="BootSkittle7.png" >
                <shortdescription>Distribution removes 2.5% of dots off each end focusing on the center proportions between 0.108 and 0.277 .</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>


  </subsection>


<subsection xml:id="subsec-BootstrapPractice">
  <title>Practice Problems</title>

<exercise xml:id="ex-bootstrap-mean-seedlings">
<title>Seedlings</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A biologist records the heights, in centimeters, of <m>5</m> seedlings:
      <m>12</m>, <m>15</m>, <m>14</m>, <m>13</m>, and <m>16</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      To study the variability of the sample mean, the biologist takes a
      bootstrap sample by sampling 5 values with replacement from the
      original data.
    </p>
    <p> To simulate this, the biologist records the seedlings heights on five cards and shuffles them. The biologist selects a card at random, records the height, and returns it to the stack. Then repeats the process until five values are recorded. Suppose bootstrap sample is: 15, 12, 16, 15, 13. 
    </p>
    <p>
      Find the mean of this bootstrap sample.
          <m> \bar{x}=\frac{71}{5}=14.2    </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      The mean of 14.2 is plotted on a dotplot and the process is repeated many times. Create a bootstrap distribution in StatKey using the original five values to create a confidence interval for a single mean. Click on Edit data and change the values to 12, 15, 14, 13, 16. Generate 1000 samples and find the mean and standard error of the distribution. Find the 90% confidence interval for the mean height of the seedlings.
    </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
    <p> The bootstrap distribution is center at the mean 14.0 with a standard error around 0.62. The 90% confidence interval is between 13 and 15 cm. Recall each dot represents a mean from 5 seedlings, with replacement. There are 1000 samples in the distribution.</p>
    <figure xml:id="SeedlingBootstrap">
            <caption>Seedling Bootstrap Distributions</caption>
            <image source="SeedlingBoot.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription>distribution of 1000 samples of size 5 centered at mean 14 and standard error of 0.625. the distribution is bell shaped with values ranging from 12 to 16..</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure> 

    </solution>
</exercise>

 <exercise xml:id="ex-bootstrap-proportion-health">
<title> Exercise</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A health researcher surveys 8 college students to determine whether they
      exercise at least three times per week. The original sample results are:
    </p>
    <p>yes, no, yes, yes, no, yes, no, yes.
    </p>
    <p>
      To create a bootstrap distribution for the sample proportion, the
      researcher takes a bootstrap sample of size 8 by sampling with
      replacement from the original responses.
    </p>
<p> A. How would the health researcher simulate this? </p> 
<p> B. Create a bootstrap distribution is StatKey for a single proportion. Edit the data for a count of 5 yes from the sample size of 8. Generate 200 samples and find the mean proportion and standard error of the distribution.</p>
<p>C. Construct a 90% confidence interval and construct 99% confidence interval. Compare the intervals. </p>
  </statement>
<solution> <title> Simulate</title>
<p> The health research could write <q>yes</q> on 5 cards and <q>no</q> on 3 cards to replicate the original sample. The research would shuffle the cards, randomly pull one card and note the  response, and then return the card to the deck. The researcher would shuffle the deck and repeat the process for a sample of 8 responses.
</p>
    <p>
      Suppose one bootstrap sample is: yes, yes, no, yes, no, yes, yes, no.
    </p>
    <p>
      Find the sample proportion of college students in this bootstrap sample who
      exercise at least three times per week.
    </p>
      <p>
      There are <m>5</m> yes responses out of <m>8</m> total responses.
    </p>
    <p>
      So the sample proportion is
      <m>  \hat{p}=\frac{5}{8}=0.625.  </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      This value is plotted on a dotplot and the process is repeated many times until a bell shaped bootstrap distribution is created.
    </p>
</solution>
<solution> <title> Bootstrap</title>
<p> With a smaller sampling of 200, there will be more variation in the possible center values. The mean proportion should be around 0.625 and a standard error of around 0.163 to 0.175. If your values are off, try adding more samples to the distribution or you can Reset Plot and create a new one. </p>
<figure xml:id="ExerciseBootstrap1">
            <caption>Exercise Bootstrap Distribution</caption>
            <image source="ExerciseBoot1.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription>distribution of 200 samples of size  centered at 0.623 and standard error of 0.168. the distribution is bell shaped with values ranging from 0.20 to 1.00.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>

</solution>
<solution> <title> Compare Intervals</title>
<p> A possible 90% confidence interval for the proportion of students who exercise at least three times per week is around 37.5% to 87.5%. </p>
<figure xml:id="ExerciseBootstrap2">
            <caption>90% Exercise Bootstrap Interval</caption>
            <image source="ExerciseBoot2.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription>distribution of 200 samples of size centered at 0.623 and standard error of 0.168. interval is 0.375 to 0.875.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>

<p> A possible 99% confidence interval for the proportion of students who exercise at least three times per week is around 25.0% to 100%. </p>
<figure xml:id="ExerciseBootstrap3">
            <caption>99% Exercise Bootstrap Interval</caption>
            <image source="ExerciseBoot3.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription>distribution of 200 samples of size  centered at 0.623 and standard error of 0.168. the interval is 0.25 to 1.00.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>

<p> By increasing the confidence level, we are including more values in the estimate for the true proportion of student who exercise at least three times per week. We are allowing for more margin of error with the  higher confidence level, yet the standard error remains the same. </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ex-bootstrap-fishing">
<title> Fish Tags</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A marine biologist wants to estimate the proportion of fish in a small
      coastal area that carry a certain harmless tag. The biologist collects an
      original sample of 10 fish and records whether each fish has the tracking
      tag. There are 4 fish with the tracking tag.
    </p>
    <p>
      To investigate how much the sample proportion might vary from sample to
      sample, the biologist uses bootstrap sampling. 
</p>
<p> A. How would the marine biologist simulate this? </p> 
<p> B. Create a bootstrap distribution is StatKey for a single proportion. Edit the data for a count of 4 trackers from the sample size of 10. Generate 200 samples and find the mean proportion and standard error of the distribution.</p>
<p>C. Construct a 95% confidence interval for the proportion of fish with the tracking tag in that coastal area. </p>
</statement>
<solution> <title> Simulate</title>
<p>The biologist repeatedly draws new samples of size 10 with replacement from the
      original sample data and then calculates the proportion of fish with a tag in the simulated sample. After many bootstrap samples are taken, the resulting proportions form a bootstrap distribution that should be symmetric and bell shaped, centered around the sample proportion of 40%.
    </p>    
<p>
      This bootstrap distribution can then be used to estimate the variability of the sample proportion and to build a confidence interval for the true population proportion.
    </p>
</solution>
<solution> <title> Bootstrap</title>
<p> In StatKey under Bootstrap Confidence Intervals, select <term> CI for Single Proportion</term> . Click on Edit Data and change count to 4 trackers from the sample size of 10. Generate 200 samples and find the mean proportion and standard error of the distribution. The distribution should be centered around 0.40 and standard error of between 0.16 to 0.17. The example below has a mean proportion of 0.410 and SE=0.161 with sample proportions ranging from 0 to 0.90. </p>
<figure xml:id="FishBootstrap1">
            <caption>Fish Tab Bootstrap Distribution</caption>
            <image source="FishBoot1.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription>distribution of 200 samples of size 10  centered at 0.41 and standard error of 0.161. the distribution is bell shaped with values ranging from 0 to 0.90.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>

</solution>
  <solution> <title> Intervals</title>
<p> A possible 95% confidence interval for the proportion of fish in the costal area with the tracking tag is between 10% and 80%. A larger confidence level will make the interval wider while a smaller confidence level will make it narrower. </p>
<figure xml:id="FishBootstrap2">
            <caption>95% Fish Tab Bootstrap Interval</caption>
            <image source="FishBoot2.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription>distribution of 200 samples of size 10  centered at 0.41 and standard error of 0.161. the interval is .10 to .80.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>

</solution> 
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ex-bootstrap-sleep">
<title> Sleep</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A health researcher wants to estimate the average number of hours of sleep
      per night for college students. The researcher collects an original sample
      of 43 students and records number of hours of sleep for the previous night.
    </p>
  <p> We will use the ClassSurvey2 data for the variable <em> Sleep</em>. 
  </p> 
    <p>  A. Describe how the researcher might create a bootstrap distribution to understand how much the sample mean sleep time might vary. 
    </p>
  <p> B. Construct a bootstrap distribution with technology to estimate with 95% confidence the mean sleep time for college students. 
  </p>
  </statement>
<solution> <title> Simulate</title> 
    <p> The researcher repeatedly creates new samples of size 43 with replacement from the original sample data. For each bootstrap sample, the researcher calculates the mean number of hours of sleep for that sample of 43 and plots the value. After many bootstrap samples are generated, the collection of sample means forms a bootstrap distribution.
    </p>
    <p>
      This bootstrap distribution can be used to estimate the variability of the sample means and to construct a confidence interval for the population mean for the number of hours of sleep for college students.
    </p>
</solution>
<solution><title> Bootstrap Interval</title> 
<p> Each dot in the bootstrap distribution is the mean from a random sample of 43 values from the original sample. This bootstrap distribution is based on 1000 samples and is center at the mean 7.118 which is close to the original sample mean of 7.121 hours of sleep. The standard error of the distribution is <m>SE=0.198</m>. The 95% confidence interval estimates the mean sleep time for college students between 6.7 to 7.5 hours. 
</p>
<figure xml:id="SleepBootstrap">
            <caption>95% Sleep Bootstrap Interval</caption>
            <image source="SleepBoot.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription>distribution of 1000 samples of size 43  centered at 7.1 and standard error of 0.198. The 95% interval is between 6.7 to 7.5 hours sleep.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>
</solution>  
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ex-bootstrap-pets">
<title>Pets</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A future veterinarian wants to estimate the average number of pets college students have, to determine job stability. The future veterinarian collects data from a sample
      of 43 college students and records number pets they currently have.
    </p>
  <p> We will use the ClassSurvey2 data for the variable <em> Pets</em>.
  </p> 
  <p> Construct a bootstrap distribution with technology to estimate with 90% confidence the mean number of pets for college students. 
  </p>
  </statement>
<solution><title> Bootstrap Interval</title> 
  <p> Each dot in the bootstrap distribution is the mean from a random sample of 43 values from the original sample. This bootstrap distribution is based on 1000 samples and is center at the mean 2.04 which is close to the original sample mean of 2.07. The distribution is approximately bell shaped even though the original sample was right skewed. The standard error of the distribution is <m>SE=0.493</m>. The 90% confidence interval estimates the mean number of pets for college students is between 1.3 to 2.9 pets. 
  </p>
  <figure xml:id="PetsBootstrap">
            <caption>90% Pets Bootstrap Interval</caption>
            <image source="PetBoot.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription>distribution of 1000 samples of size 43  centered at 2.04 pets and standard error of 0.493. The 90% interval is between 1.3 to 2.9 pets. </shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>
</solution>  
</exercise> 

<exercise xml:id="ex-bootstrap-credits">
<title>Credit Hours</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      An admissions counselor wants to estimate the average number of credit hours taken by college students in the fall semester. The admissions counselor collects data from a sample of 43 college students and records number credits they are taking that semester.
    </p>
<p> We will use the ClassSurvey2 data for the variable <em> Credit hours</em>.
</p> 
    <p> Construct a bootstrap distribution with technology to estimate with 95% confidence the mean credit hours college students take. 
</p>
</statement>
<solution><title> Bootstrap Interval</title> 
<p> Each dot in the bootstrap distribution is the mean from a random sample of 43 values from the original sample. This bootstrap distribution is based on 1000 samples and is center at the mean 15.04 credits which is close to the original sample mean of 15.047. The standard error of the distribution is <m>SE=0.293</m>. The 95% confidence interval estimates the mean credit hours for college students is between 14.488 to 15.651 credits. 
</p>
<figure xml:id="CreditHoursBootstrap">
            <caption>95% Credit Hours Bootstrap Interval</caption>
            <image source="CreditBoot.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription>distribution of 1000 samples of size 43  centered at 15 credits and standard error of 0.293. The 95% interval is between 14.488 and 15.651 credits. </shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>

</solution>  
</exercise> 

<exercise xml:id="ex-bootstrap-tattoos">
<title>Tattoos</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A tattoo artist wants to estimate the average number of tattoos college students have, to determine job stability. The tattoo artist collects data from a sample  of 43 college students and records number tattoos they currently have.
    </p>
<p> We will use the ClassSurvey2 data for the variable <em> Tattoos</em>.
</p> 
    <p> Construct a bootstrap distribution with technology to estimate with 95% confidence the mean number of tattoos for college students. 
</p>
</statement>
<solution><title> Bootstrap Interval</title> 
<p> Each dot in the bootstrap distribution is the mean from a random sample of 43 values from the original sample. This bootstrap distribution is based on 1000 samples and is center at the mean 1.38 tattoos which is close to the original sample mean of 1.395. The distribution is approximately bell shaped even though the original sample was right skewed with up to 12 tattoos. The standard error of the distribution is <m>SE=0.391</m>. The 95% confidence interval estimates the mean number of tattoos for college students is between 0.7 to 2.2 tattoos. 
</p>
<figure xml:id="TattoosBootstrap">
            <caption>95% Tattoo Bootstrap Interval</caption>
            <image source="TattooBoot.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription>distribution of 1000 samples of size 43  centered at 1.38 tattoos and standard error of 0.391. The 95% interval is between 0.7 and 2.2 tattoos. </shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>

</solution>  
</exercise> 



  </subsection>




